SIMPLE: fume
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fume
<hw>Fume</hw> <pr>(f⟦umac⟧m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>fumus</ets>; akin to Skr. <ets>dh⟦umac⟧ma</ets> smoke,
<ets>dh⟦umac⟧</ets> to shake, fan a flame, cf. Gr. <grk>qy`ein</grk> to
sacrifice, storm, rage, <grk>qy`mon</grk>, <grk>qy`mos</grk>, thyme, and
perh. to E. dust: cf. OF. <ets>fum</ets> smoke, F.
<ets>fum⟦eacute⟧e</ets>. Cf. <er>Dust</er>, <pos>n.</pos>,
<er>Femerell</er>, <er>Thyme</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Exhalation;
volatile matter (esp. noxious vapor or smoke) ascending in a dense body;
smoke; vapor; reek; <as>as, the <ex>fumes</ex> of
tobacco</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>fumes</qex> of new shorn hay.</q> <rj><qau>T.
Warton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>fumes</qex> of undigested wine.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Rage or excitement which deprives the mind of
self-control; <as>as, the fumes of passion</as>.</def>
<rj><au>South.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Anything vaporlike, unsubstantial, or airy; idle
conceit; vain imagination.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A show of fumes and fancies.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The incense of praise; inordinate
flattery.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To smother him with <qex>fumes</qex> and eulogies.</q>
<rj><qau>Burton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Metal.)</fld> <def>Solid material deposited by
condensation of fumes; <as>as, lead <ex>fume</ex> (a grayish powder
chiefly lead sulphate)</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>In a fume</b></col>, <cd>in ill temper, esp. from
impatience.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fume</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fume
<hw>Fume</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Fumed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Fuming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>fumer</ets>, L.
<ets>fumare</ets> to smoke. See <er>Fume</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To smoke; to throw off fumes, as in combustion or
chemical action; to rise up, as vapor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where the golden altar <qex>fumed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Silenus lay,⟦br⟧
Whose constant cups lay <qex>fuming</qex> to his brain.</q>
<rj><qau>Roscommon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be as in a mist; to be dulled and
stupefied.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Keep his brain <qex>fuming</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To pass off in fumes or vapors.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their parts are kept from <qex>fuming</qex> away by their
fixity.</q> <rj><qau>Cheyne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To be in a rage; to be hot with anger.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He frets, he <qex>fumes</qex>, he stares, he stamps the
ground.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>While her mother did fret, and her father did <qex>fume</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To fume away</b></col>, <cd>to give way to excitement and
displeasure; to storm; also, to pass off in fumes.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fume</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fume
<hw>Fume</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To expose to the action
of fumes; to treat with vapors, smoke, etc.; <as>as, to bleach straw by
<ex>fuming</ex> it with sulphur</as>; to fill with fumes, vapors, odors,
etc., as a room.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She <qex>fumed</qex> the temple with an odorous flame.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To praise inordinately; to flatter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They demi-deify and <qex>fume</qex> him so.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To throw off in vapor, or as in the form of
vapor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The heat will <qex>fume</qex> away most of the scent.</q>
<rj><qau>Montimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How vicious hearts <qex>fume</qex> frenzy to the brain!</q>
<rj><qau>Young.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fumed oak</ent>⟦br⟧
